<dl id="n10054g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10054g">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10054g"> 54(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> reverse</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> Cette voiture avait une force d&apos;impulsion si consid&eacute;rable, que, n&apos;&eacute;tant pas convenablement guid&eacute;e, elle <mark>renversa</mark> un pan de mur. Cette machine remarquable &agrave; beaucoup d&apos;&eacute;gards, que son auteur d&eacute;signait sous le nom de <i>fardier &agrave; vapeur</i> (fig. 60), existe encore actuellement au Conservatoire national des Arts et M&eacute;tiers. Elle &eacute;tait expos&eacute;e au Palais des Arts lib&eacute;raux, &agrave; l&apos;Exposition universelle de 1889. <font color="green">[This wagon had such power of impulsion, that, when it was driven properly, it knocked over a wall. This machine, so remarkable in many ways, which its inventor called the steam chariot (fig. 60), still exists at the National Conservatory of the Arts and Professions. It was exhibited at the Palace of the liberal Arts at the Universal Exposition of 1889]</font> <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) 162</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Of the French verbs <i>reverser</i> and <i>renverser</i>, the former means &lsquo;to transfer&rsquo; and the latter &lsquo;to reverse.&rsquo; </mm> </dd></dl>
